      "message": "[🟡 Suggestions] Line 351: The STUN server validator splits on the first \u0027:\u0027 character, so valid IPv6 literals such as \u0027[2001:db8::1]:3478\u0027 or \u00272001:db8::1\u0027 are rejected. SIP connectivity settings should not make IPv6 STUN servers impossible to configure. Parse bracketed IPv6 host:port explicitly and only treat a colon as a port separator when there is a single host/port separator, or use URLComponents/Network framework parsing.\n```suggestion\nstatic func isValidStunServer(_ value: String) -\u003e Bool {\n    let trimmed \u003d value.trimmingCharacters(in: .whitespacesAndNewlines)\n    guard !trimmed.isEmpty else { return false }\n\n    if trimmed.hasPrefix(\"[\") {\n        guard let end \u003d trimmed.firstIndex(of: \"]\") else { return false }\n        let host \u003d trimmed[trimmed.index(after: trimmed.startIndex)..\u003cend]\n        let remainder \u003d trimmed[trimmed.index(after: end)...]\n        guard !host.isEmpty else { return false }\n        if remainder.isEmpty { return true }\n        guard remainder.hasPrefix(\":\"), remainder.count \u003e 1 else { return false }\n        return isValid(String(remainder.dropFirst()), in: publishedPortRange)\n    }\n\n    let parts \u003d trimmed.split(separator: \":\", omittingEmptySubsequences: false)\n    if parts.count \u003d\u003d 1 { return true }\n    guard parts.count \u003d\u003d 2, !parts[0].isEmpty else { return false }\n    return isValid(String(parts[1]), in: publishedPortRange)\n}\n```",
